            "answer_text": "Everyone you ask will give you lots of different numbers but if you do a bit of research, instead of asking the question on Quora, you will discover that novellas are usually up to 40,000 words, which work out to some 160-pages, based on an average of 250 words per page. To know for sure, you will need to consult with publishers on what is the minimum wordage they accept for their company. Standard novellas usually hovered around the 120-page mark though most are now about 200-pages. They are essentially long short stories that are still divided into chapters. Now you need to stop thinking in terms of page-count and realign your mind to think in terms of word-count. Every word processing software will have a feature that will track your word count. MSWord has a word-count and when I write I always have that feature active. I believe that OpenOffice Writer and LibreOffice Writer also have that feature under \u201ctools\u201d. Those two are free and an awesome and great alternative to MSWord. They work just fine and can do everything Word can do. You also need to stop corralling yourself in a specific length of something you are writing, unless you are a journalist for a newspaper or a magazine where the editor asks for a specific number of words. This is often calculated by the column-inch that will be needed to be used for that story. If you are just writing a story, then understand that your story will only be as long as it needs to be, to tell the story properly. Less than what is needed can disappoint the reader, and more can bore them. Never approach a story by saying to yourself, \u201cthis will be a novella, or this will be an epic\u201d. Just outline your story, create your characters and the crises they will have to deal with, and take into account the level of creative writing you will need to tell the story. If may want just a basic story, or you may wish to approach it as something literary, and this will affect the end word-count. ",
